# Ship testable work to `main`

When a task changes **runtime behavior**, **APIs**, **database assumptions**, or anything you would reasonably **verify on the deployed site**, finish by **committing and pushing** so the owner can test on the live environment tied to GitHub `main`.

## Do this before ending the task

1. **`git status`** — confirm intended files are changed; avoid committing secrets or local-only files.
2. **`git add`** only what belongs in the commit.
3. **`git commit`** with a short, accurate message (what changed and why).
4. **`git push origin main`** (use another branch only if the owner asked).

## If push fails

- Read the error (auth, non-fast-forward, hooks).
- Fix or tell the owner what blocked the push; do not claim the deploy is updated until `main` is pushed successfully.

## When to skip

- Read-only exploration, docs-only nits the owner did not ask to ship, or the owner explicitly says not to push yet.
